		  		<p class = "cent_text big_print"><strong>Childhood</strong></p> 
				<p>At an early age, Bryce Cheng was tasked with the heavy burden of upholding the prestigious
				Cheng Dynasty's legacy. As the oldest of the "twin dragons," Bryce was tasked with "making the Cheng
				Family great again" in the then foreign continent of North America. Alongside his younger brother,
				Darrell, Bryce underwent integral training at the University of Washington Academy for Young Scholars to
				acquire the skills necessary to survive in the brutal capitalist world of the United States.</p>
				<p class = "cent_text big_print"><strong>Rice to Greatness</strong></p> 
				<p>After receiving a "small" loan of 500-million dollars from the Cheng family fortune,

				Bryce established a strong foothold in the American economy by investing in construction through his

				newfound company, The Cheng Organization. Through The Cheng Organization, Bryce monopolized the market

				for construction and property development (twice running Donald Trump bankrupt). In addition, Bryce

				was able to curb downsizing through lobbying the U.S. government with his now 50-billion dollar net worth.</p>
				<p class = "cent_text big_print"><strong>Enlightenment and Future Investment in Philanthropy</strong></p>
				<p>After monopolizing the construction market through his trademark aggressive negotiating strategy, Bryce Cheng was now a leading figure in the

				American business world earning himself a position at the top of the Fortune 500. However, Cheng was haunted by the

				effects of his success in the construction market after witnessing the countless competitors that lay

				bankrupt as a result of his rise. In order to cope with his burdensome guilt, Bryce Cheng, with the help of Darrel Cheng 
				(CEO of Cheng Consolidated Entertainment Facilities), merged to found the Cheng Foundation.</p>

